articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: U.S. Secretary of State Antony Blinken arrived in Saudi Arabia on Monday, the first stop in a broader trip to the Middle East, aimed at discussing with Arab partners post-war Gaza and to press Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to take the concrete and tangible steps U.S. President Joe Biden demanded this month to improve the dire humanitarian situation in Gaza.
articles.title: US Secretary of state Antony Blinken arrives in Saudi Arabia

articles.author: Nidal Al-Mughrabi
articles.description: Israeli air strikes on three houses in the southern Gaza city of Rafah killed 13 people and wounded many others, medics said on Monday.
articles.title: At least 13 Palestinians killed in Israeli strikes on Rafah, medical officials say

articles.author: Julia Harte
articles.description: Columbia University's president said on Monday that talks with pro-Palestinian protesters who began camping on the Ivy League campus two weeks ago had failed, and urged them to voluntarily disperse, without saying what would happen if they did not.
articles.title: Columbia University urges pro-Palestinian protesters to disperse after failed talks

articles.author: Alistair Smout, Andy Bruce
articles.description: Scotland's leader Humza Yousaf resigned on Monday, further opening the door to the UK opposition Labour Party to regain ground in its former Scottish heartlands in a national election expected later this year.
articles.title: Scotland's Humza Yousaf resigns as country's leader

articles.author: Pavel Polityuk
articles.description: President Volodymyr Zelenskiy said on Monday that vital U.S. weapons were starting to arrive in Ukraine in small amounts and that the process needed to move faster as advancing Russian forces were trying to take advantage.
articles.title: Ukraine's Zelenskiy urges US to speed up weapons deliveries

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Austrian prosecutors said on Monday they are investigating far-right leader Herbert Kickl on suspicion of breach of trust for allegedly using public funds to take out media advertising in exchange for favourable party coverage when he was a minister.
articles.title: Austrian prosecutors investigate far-right leader, suspect breach of trust

articles.author: Phil Stewart, Daphne Psaledakis
articles.description: The U.S. military's cost estimate to build a pier off Gaza to deliver humanitarian aid has risen to $320 million, a U.S. defense official and a source familiar with the matter told Reuters.
articles.title: Exclusive: US military's pier in Gaza to cost $320 million

articles.author: Alexandra Valencia
articles.description: Ecuador's foreign ministry said on Monday it has sued Mexico at the International Court of Justice in The Hague, asking it to find that Mexico's decision to grant asylum to former Ecuadorean vice-president Jorge Glas violated international law.
articles.title: Ecuador sues Mexico at ICJ over granting asylum to former VP

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: Argentina's SOEA oilseed workers' union kicked off a strike on Monday to protest a labor reform bill backed by President Javier Milei, which hit the lower house floor for debate shortly before.
articles.title: Argentina oilseed union strikes to protest Milei labor reforms

articles.author: Reuters
articles.description: A female Georgian member of parliament hit a male colleague with a water bottle on Monday as tempers ran high during discussion of a contentious "foreign agents" law.
articles.title: Lawmakers scuffle again in Georgia over 'foreign agent' bill
